{"pageProps":{"post":{"_createdAt":"2022-06-21T12:10:46Z","_id":"1b719d68-3b05-40b2-b392-5973efeb0151","author":{"image":{"_type":"image","asset":{"_ref":"image-339f8e320ddfad52225d31a181b162996e1c02d1-876x876-png","_type":"reference"}},"name":"üëæ Game Master"},"body":[{"_key":"9fa904b2f37d","_type":"block","children":[{"_key":"dfe56488d0720","_type":"span","marks":[],"text":"Pre-Required Knowledge"}],"markDefs":[],"style":"h1"},{"_key":"62b66fef1d71","_type":"block","children":[{"_key":"ee7ce7b22a650","_type":"span","marks":[],"text":"The Efficient Frontier is a financial theory frequently applied in risk management-related areas. But to understand the concepts and applications of the Efficient Frontier, some previous knowledge of asset‚Äôs risk and return is required. It is recommended to read and understand the following concepts before digging into this article:"}],"markDefs":[],"style":"normal"},{"_key":"cfbc1d892271","_type":"block","children":[{"_key":"ff0fa5352b740","_type":"span","marks":["ddbb42543cf8"],"text":"Mean, Variance and Covariance"}],"level":1,"listItem":"bullet","markDefs":[{"_key":"ddbb42543cf8","_type":"link","href":"https://www.notion.so/Mean-Variance-and-Covariance-06b2968a95ba4fb587bb801cd56f3fee"}],"style":"normal"},{"_key":"c4945be8d002","_type":"block","children":[{"_key":"0217ca3ec09e0","_type":"span","marks":["9bf5963d36dc"],"text":"Standard Deviation and Correlation"}],"level":1,"listItem":"bullet","markDefs":[{"_key":"9bf5963d36dc","_type":"link","href":"https://www.notion.so/Standard-Deviation-and-Correlation-dd0c6014644d422ca80677fd66737a8a"}],"style":"normal"},{"_key":"58318006db74","_type":"block","children":[{"_key":"9034add4ff220","_type":"span","marks":["677d6c6dae49"],"text":"Risk-Return Tradeoff & Volatility"}],"level":1,"listItem":"bullet","markDefs":[{"_key":"677d6c6dae49","_type":"link","href":"https://www.notion.so/Risk-Return-Tradeoff-Volatility-08ac9e874e344c3e89828a98220fa774"}],"style":"normal"},{"_key":"fa5b2fa97e88","_type":"block","children":[{"_key":"01efcc2a497c0","_type":"span","marks":["b4ffd846ae45"],"text":"Risk-Averse, Risk-Neutral, and Risk-Seeking"}],"level":1,"listItem":"bullet","markDefs":[{"_key":"b4ffd846ae45","_type":"link","href":"https://www.notion.so/Risk-Averse-Risk-Neutral-and-Risk-Seeking-b0ff3c17c5c440baa5c01ec4be8478bf"}],"style":"normal"},{"_key":"21ae88d6ce22","_type":"block","children":[{"_key":"aefa655ac0a60","_type":"span","marks":["b8d20d7022b4"],"text":"Modern Portfolio Theory"}],"level":1,"listItem":"bullet","markDefs":[{"_key":"b8d20d7022b4","_type":"link","href":"https://www.notion.so/Modern-Portfolio-Theory-ef81e3cdcb0b4359a1255f573dfb4b8e"}],"style":"normal"},{"_key":"f4747b1d74e3","_type":"block","children":[{"_key":"7798d64bf1320","_type":"span","marks":["3c3744e58835"],"text":"Efficient Market Hypothesis (EMH)"}],"level":1,"listItem":"bullet","markDefs":[{"_key":"3c3744e58835","_type":"link","href":"https://www.notion.so/Efficient-Market-Hypothesis-EMH-d76f726e5b924457a4a322fa7052602d"}],"style":"normal"},{"_key":"9ecd512ea5bd","_type":"block","children":[{"_key":"fe1faf59ee0b0","_type":"span","marks":[],"text":"Although the Efficient Frontier is often viewed as a cornerstone of the Modern Portfolio Theory (and the Efficient Market Hypothesis), understanding these two concepts before reading the Efficient Frontier is beneficial to building a more thorough understanding of risk in finance."}],"markDefs":[],"style":"normal"},{"_key":"434600ca65f8","_type":"block","children":[{"_key":"70316b6a12850","_type":"span","marks":[],"text":"Key Concepts"}],"markDefs":[],"style":"h1"},{"_key":"6e2cb32a1a4a","_type":"block","children":[{"_key":"92d1e59544920","_type":"span","marks":[],"text":"Harry Markowitz first introduced the concept of an Efficient Frontier in his work "},{"_key":"92d1e59544921","_type":"span","marks":["em"],"text":"Portfolio Selection"},{"_key":"92d1e59544922","_type":"span","marks":[],"text":". He promoted the strategy of using mean-variance optimization to find the most ‚Äúefficient (AKA optimal) portfolio (asset combination).‚Äù In other words, portfolios located on the Efficient Frontier often maximize the risk-adjusted return. Given a certain risk profile, these sets of portfolios on the Efficient Frontier output the highest return rate than any other portfolio combination. Given a certain standard deviation, these sets of portfolios on the Efficient Frontier also give the biggest expected return."}],"markDefs":[],"style":"normal"},{"_key":"bd9461e15365","_type":"image","asset":{"_ref":"image-0b4ddd53f1862599af7c18697eb9f41306ad2590-1024x683-png","_type":"reference"}},{"_key":"7a1f9bd01be7","_type":"block","children":[{"_key":"1e051510a5080","_type":"span","marks":["em"],"text":"Harry Markowitz. Photo source: "},{"_key":"1e051510a5081","_type":"span","marks":["3908123117b5","em"],"text":"https://www.matsonmoney.com/wp-content/uploads/2019/10/Academic-Advisory-Board-Matson-Money-Harry-M-Markowitz-1024x683.jpg"}],"markDefs":[{"_key":"3908123117b5","_type":"link","href":"https://www.matsonmoney.com/wp-content/uploads/2019/10/Academic-Advisory-Board-Matson-Money-Harry-M-Markowitz-1024x683.jpg"}],"style":"normal"},{"_key":"03804a1db6ba","_type":"block","children":[{"_key":"38efca0cef0c0","_type":"span","marks":[],"text":"Application: How to Find the Efficient Frontier?"}],"markDefs":[],"style":"h1"},{"_key":"2e22e55617f6","_type":"block","children":[{"_key":"fd1705a9919e0","_type":"span","marks":[],"text":"Under most cases, the Efficient Frontier is plotted in an x-y plane, with an x-value marking expected return and a y-value marking risk (standard deviation). Every possible combination of assets (i.e., stocks) can be plotted in this x-y plane, and the combinations on the outer layer are the so-called ‚ÄúEfficient portfolio combinations.‚Äù This entire outer layer is defined as the Efficient Frontier."}],"markDefs":[],"style":"normal"},{"_key":"e0ba813fb131","_type":"block","children":[{